Lord Clarendon, vol i 215. says, that the parliamentary party were not agreed about the entire
abolition of episcopaey: They were only the root and branch men, as they were called, who insisted on
that measure. But those who were willing to retain bishops, insisted on reducing their authority to a
low ebb; as well as on abolishing the ceremonies of worship and vestments of the clergy. The con-
troversy, therefore, between the parties was almost wholly theological, and that of the most frivolous
and ridiculous kind.
